title: For Sale:  Walther Model 8 - 1st variant
postcontent: This is a Walther Model 8, 1st variant. The serial number places the guns manufatured date around 1925/1926. Bore - Strong rifling left. Caliber is 6,35mm (.25 ACP to us Americans)Grips - Hard rubber with enamel medallions. These are in great condition and are often lost or broken on these old pistols.Finish - Original finish, there isn't a tremendous bluing left on the slide, but a solid amount left on the frame. Good amount of bluing left on trigger guard and trigger. This gun has not been refinished and has nice, crisp rollmarks, and a patina consistant with the age of the pistol. Magazine - Original mag with "Walther" printed on the bottom. History - There are three total variants for this model, with this being variant No. 1. These pistols were produced from 1920 to approximately 1940, with U.S. Walther collector Marschall estimating that approximately 145k being made. The Model 8 was often carried by member's of the German officers during WW2, and as a backup gun by tank crewman and pilots. The Model 8 was also one of the two pistols found by Hitler after he killed himself. I'm looking for $400 OBO. No trades please.Please text any questions to Eight Six Five 712 Eight Five Six Four

title: For Sale:  Kimber of Oregon 6mm PPC very rare & Dies
postcontent: Will ship to a USA Licensed Fire Arms dealer by UPS for $50.00. Based on recent internet sales: Estimated retail value, in “near new”, very collectible condition = ($2,000. to $2,450.) The sale price includes Hornady reloading dies and Redding 7.62 X 39 Russian case resizing dies (neck down to 6mm). In 1987, Kimber of Oregon announced a new edition to their line of rifles, the Model 84 Ultra Varmint, and offered the rifle in a small group of calibers: .222 REM, 6MM PPC, 6X45MM, and .223 REM. In 1988 and 1989, the dealer price lists offered the Ultra Varmint in a different group of calibers: .17 REM, .221 REM and .223 REM. In 1990, Kimber listed only the .222 REM and .223 REM calibers for the Ultra Varmint rifles. In 1991, the year that Kimber closed their doors due to bankruptcy, Kimber listed the Ultra Varmint calibers as .17 REM, .22 Hornet, .222 REM, .22-250 REM, and .223 REM. The 6MM PPC was listed as a factory offered caliber in the Ultra Varmint only for the introductory year, 1987......and it NEVER WAS listed as an available caliber for the Ultra Varmint rifles after that year. How many 6MM PPCs exist? We do not know. We do know that Kimber built a very few Ultra Varmint rifles chambered in the wonderfully accurate 6MM PPC. THIS IS ONE OF THOSE RARE RIFLES!! The Ultra Varmint was (and is) a varmint style of rifle designed to tolerate inhospitable field conditions while delivering consistent accuracy. Starting with a laminated birch stock with a straight comb and no cheekpiece, Kimber added 20 lines-per-inch checkering, a curved rubber butt pad, a widened forearm designed to provide stability, a “medium-heavy” stainless steel 24 inch varmint weight barrel, a matte blue receiver and trigger guard, a three dimensional steel grip cap in matte blue finish, and two post-style sling swivel studs. This Kimber Ultra Varmiter is a single shot 6MM PPC wearing serial number “6PPC468”, with the Heavy Barrel with its bead blasted matte finish and its 0.6875 inch muzzle. This rifle has the Kimber disc safety and the Model 84 standard bolt, with its Mauser-style extractor and matte blue handle and shroud. A correct one piece, matte blue finish, factory provided and installed Kimber scope ring mounting base (no scope rings included) is on the top of the receiver waiting for your choice of scopes and mounting rings. Weight: ~7 pounds 12 ounces. OAL: ~42.5 inches. LOP: ~13 5/8 inches. This rifle is in “as new” condition. Kimber Ultra Varmint rifles do not come to the market often, and almost never are they seen in this “as new” condition. Ultra Varmint examples in the 6MM PPC chambering are very rare. SN “6PPC468” I only shot the M84 to check that it's functions were ok and did not shoot at targets and have just stored it in my collection or rare rifles. I believe that the heavy stainless steel barrel is free-floated in the rigid Birch laminated stock. (the stock's wood has a dark stain and does not look like Birch). So, driving nails, (with custom loads), at 100 yards, should be no problem.
